    "attributes": {
        "action": "Amend 'Public Health (Control of Disease) Act 1984' to legalise human composting",
        "additional_details": "After death care is a very personal preference and the more choices that people have, the better.\r\nTraditional burial and cremation, until recently were the only funerary options. Both are environmentally damaging.\r\nGreen burials are another great choice, but still take up valuable land.\r\nBeing able to renourish soil or a tree with the compost of a loved one is the ultimate option in returning from where we all came.",
        "background": "The Public Health Act includes provision for \"Green burials\" where human remains are buried in a biodegradable casket but \"composting\" has not yet been legalised under these regulations.\r\nHuman composting happens above ground in a vessel that allows the body to become compost in 30-60 days.",
